#1 Sigmoid cancer
Mrs. Martinez is a 38-year-old female who since around Christmastime has had intermittent abdominal cramping, change in bowel habits with ribbon-like stools.  She had one episode of blood in the toilet bowl.  She has lost 25 pounds intentionally due to exercise and dieting.  No abnormal weight-loss.  Appetite good.  Colonoscopy March 22, 2010, was only to 20 cm where a strictured tumor affect noted.  This was biopsied.  I am told this was cancer, but I do not have the outside pathology.  A CT-scan on March 25, 2010, of abdomen and pelvis showed upper sigmoid colon involving approximately 5- to 6-cm in length mural mass.  There was also adjacent to this in the posterior pericolonic fat a conglomeration of regional lymph node metastases.  This extended into the lower retroperitoneum at the level of the aortic bifurcation.  There were two small low-attenuation lesions in the posterior right hepatic lobe, indeterminate, but suspicious for hepatic metastases.  Patient now comes to Blakely House Health Care Center for further evaluation of the above.

